The Accident Investigation Bureau (AIB) Nigeria has expressed readiness to investigate other modes of transportation, apart from air incidents and accidents. Although the bureau’s core function is to investigate aircraft accidents or serious incidents with a view to preventing future recurrence of similar accident or incident, efforts are being made to add the road accident investigation and other modes of transportation to its duties. Explaining how far AIB has gone with its plans to expand the scope of incident and accident investigation to other modes of transportation in the country, the bureau stated that they are set to commence with that mandate as soon as they are empowered by the law. Commissioner/chief executive officer, AIB, Engr Akin Olateru, who informed about their readiness said, it will start once the bill is approved by the national assembly and the president. Engr Olateru said:  “We are set out to investigate air accident but there is a proposed bill at the National Assembly to include other modes of transport. It has passed the second reading at the House of Representatives, we are waiting for public hearing. At the senate, we are waiting for second reading and public hearing.” He said AIB is still doing what it ought to do normally, saying, “COVID-19 or not; we still ensure that we deliver on our mandate, we ensure we do what we have to do, but the only problem we have is funding. COVID-19 has affected our revenues greatly.” 